<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="514" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,151,464]" pageId="13" pageNumber="514">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,295,320]" pageId="13" pageNumber="514">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[325,541,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Platypezidae" genus="Callomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="514" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arnaudi">
<emphasis box="[325,541,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="514">Callomyia arnaudi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to the Nearctic species 
<taxonomicName box="[1028,1208,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Platypezidae" genus="Callomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="514" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gilloglyorum">
<emphasis box="[1028,1047,296,319]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="514">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1063,1208,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="514">gilloglyorum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the Palaearctic species 
<taxonomicName box="[238,328,332,357]" class="Insecta" family="Platypezidae" genus="Callomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="514" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dives">
<emphasis box="[238,257,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="514">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[270,328,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="514">dives</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Chandler" authorityName="Chandler" box="[381,618,332,357]" class="Insecta" family="Platypezidae" genus="Callomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="514" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saibhira">
<emphasis box="[381,400,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="514">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[413,506,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="514">saibhira</emphasis>
Chandler
</taxonomicName>
, as shown in the strict consensus tree (
<figureCitation box="[1047,1131,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 79" captionStartId="48.[151,250,1867,1889]" captionTargetBox="[152,1430,205,1837]" captionTargetId="figure@48.[151,1436,195,1845]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURE 79. Strict consensus tree of the 136 most parsimonious cladograms of the world species of Callomyia and outgroups, produced by the analysis of the data matrix in Table 2. Bremer support values are listed above each internode. The Oriental species, Callomyia coei Kessel and C. triangulata Tkoč, were excluded from the analysis because they are only known from females." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/271502/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="514">
Fig. 
<number box="[1099,1131,332,356]" pageId="13" pageNumber="514" value="79.0">79</number>
</figureCitation>
). The male terminalia of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Platypezidae" genus="Callomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="514" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arnaudi">
<emphasis box="[1410,1429,333,356]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="514">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[151,240,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="514">arnaudi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are most similar to the terminalia of 
<taxonomicName box="[690,820,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Platypezidae" genus="Callomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="514" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saibhira">
<emphasis box="[690,709,368,391]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="514">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[727,820,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="514">saibhira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(comparison based on description and figures of 
<taxonomicName authority="in Chandler" authorityName="in Chandler" authorityYear="2001" class="Insecta" family="Platypezidae" genus="Callomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="514" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saibhira">
<emphasis box="[1410,1429,368,391]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="514">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[151,244,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="514">saibhira</emphasis>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="Chandler" box="[290,651,404,429]" pageId="13" pageNumber="514" refString="Chandler, P. J. (2001) The flat-footed flies (Diptera: Opetiidae and Platypezidae) of Europe. Fauna Entomologica Scandinavica, 36, 1 - 276." type="journal article" year="2001">
Chandler (
<number box="[412,472,404,428]" pageId="13" pageNumber="514" value="2001.0">2001</number>
, figs 
<number box="[542,644,404,428]" pageId="13" pageNumber="514" value="239.0" valueMax="240.0" valueMin="238.0">238−240</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Tkoc" box="[715,1111,404,429]" pageId="13" pageNumber="514" refString="Tkoc, M. &amp; Rohacek, J. (2014) Diversity, distribution and biology of Romanian flat-footed flies (Diptera, Opetiidae and Platypezidae) with taxonomic notes on Callomyia saibhira Chandler. ZooKeys, 459, 95 - 118. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 459.8376" type="journal article" year="2014">
Tkoč &amp; Roháček (
<number box="[936,996,404,428]" pageId="13" pageNumber="514" value="2014.0">2014</number>
, fig. 
<number box="[1062,1092,404,428]" pageId="13" pageNumber="514" value="10.0">10</number>
))
</bibRefCitation>
. However, the thoracic and abdominal colour patterns and shape of the hypandrial process differ between these two species.
</paragraph>
